This paper is about game theory and decision making, which are central topics in computer science. The paper discusses the distinction between strategic and nonstrategic behavior, which is a key concept in game theory. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.GT (Computer Science - Game Theory). Additionally, the paper proposes a new formal characterization of nonstrategic behavior, which involves modeling decision-making processes, and thus could also fit into categories such as cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the bounded rationality of nonstrategic agents, which could be relevant to categories such as cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.CR (Cryptography and Security).
